\begin{abstract}
Pronunciation assessment and its application in computer-aided pronunciation training (CAPT) have seen impressive progress in recent years. End-to-end neural network models have replaced traditional systems, and various resources in multiple languages have been proposed. However, many of these systems are thought to be opaque in defining what wrong pronunciation is, with a wide range of spectrum, ranging from unintelligible speech to native-like speech. This has led researchers to analyze phonetic and prosodic features to build an automatic model for scoring speech learning accuracy. In this survey paper, we review methods in pronunciation assessment, categorize the main challenges in prominent research trends, highlight existing limitations, resources, and point to potential directions for future work.
\end{abstract}

