The increment of the development of CAPT systems is fueled by the rising demand for foreign language learning along with the tide of globalization. This surge has led to extensive research and development efforts in the field. 
There are several papers summarizing the advancements in automatic error detection in pronunciation training \cite{eskenazi1999using, eskenazi2009overview, witt2012automatic, li2016mispronunciation, nancy2016}. In the realm of ASR for L2 pronunciation, Eskenazi provides a thorough examination of its potentials and limitations, showcasing its practical implementation within an interface developed at CMU \cite{eskenazi1999using}. Building upon this foundation, Eskenazi further delves into the historical progression and state-of-the-art methodologies of automatic scoring, with a notable emphasis on modalities of interaction, associated algorithms, and the challenges \cite{eskenazi2009overview}. Witt's comprehensive overview presents a meticulous exploration of automatic error detection, encompassing various scoring methodologies and an assessment of commercial CAPT systems \cite{witt2012automatic}. Although Witt's work has certain limitations towards phoneme error detection, \cite{nancy2016} provides a research summary, focusing on both phoneme errors and prosodic error detection. In this comprehensive review paper, we provide a thorough review of methods employed in the realm of pronunciation assessment for both phonemic and prosodic errors detection. We aim to categorize the primary challenges observed within prominent research trends, while also shedding light on existing limitations and available resources. Additionally, we will explore potential directions for future work. 
This paper organizes the literature into distinct themes. In \textbf{Section 2}, we delve into various components that contribute to pronunciation, while also highlighting different types of pronunciation errors. \textbf{Section 3} focuses on the discussion of diverse datasets utilized in pronunciation assessment, emphasizing the intricacies involved in annotating data and exploring potential augmentations techniques for to generate more data. Moving forward to \textbf{Section 4}, we examine the range of technical features and approaches employed for assessing pronunciation. In \textbf{Section 5}, we explore the evaluation metrics commonly used. Finally, \textbf{Section 6} addresses additional challenges and provides insights into future directions for further advancement.

