\subsection{Segmental Errors}
Segmental errors involve the production of individual sounds, such as vowels, consonants, and consonant clusters and it can be subdivided into three types: substitution, deletion, and insertion. The causes leading to segmental errors can be attributed to several factors including language transfer, incorrect letter-to-sound conversion, and misreading of text prompts \cite{meng2007deriving, qian2010capturing, kartushina2014effects, li2016mispronunciation}. For example, L2 learners tend to substitute a phone in the target language that is absent in their native language with a similar phone. For instance, Arabic learners of English may replace the sound /p/ with the sound /b/ resulting in pronouncing "cab" as "cap".

% such us $/b, d, g/$, so "cap" for "cab" for Cantonese learners, and $/p, b/$, so "berfect" for "perfect". 

Deletion errors occur when a sound is left out altogether. For example, Hindi learners might say "cah" for "car" \cite{zhao2018l2}. 


% Chinese learners of English might say "tee" for "tree" because the Chinese language does not have the /r/ phoneme. 
Insertion errors manifest when an additional sound is introduced into a word. English learners may pronounce the n sound at the end of words like "bon" in French because they are used to pronouncing final consonants in English. In English, many words end in consonants, such as "can", "man", and "sun". So, when English learners learn French, they may mistakenly apply this rule to French words and pronounce the final n sound in words like "bon".

Another factor contributing to segmental errors is incorrect letter-to-sound conversion. When encountering unfamiliar words, L2 learners may rely on guessing to pronounce them. Or simply learners may misread certain words, resulting in pronunciation errors.

\subsection{Supra-segmental Errors}
% Supra-segmental features are features that affect the pronunciation of a word or sentence as a whole, such as stress, intonation, and rhythm. Supra-segmental errors involve the production of larger units of sound. In terms of intelligibility, Supra-segmental features are often more important \cite{raux2002automatic}, as they can help to convey the meaning of a sentence. 

% Suprasegmental errors can also be further subdivided into three types: stress, intonation, and rhythm errors. 

Supra-segmental features encompass elements that influence the pronunciation of an entire word or sentence, including stress, rhythm, and intonation. Errors related to supra-segmental features involve the production of larger sound units. In terms of intelligibility, supra-segmental features have been recognized as particularly significant \cite{raux2002automatic}, and especially for tone target languages \cite{dahmen2023prosodic}, as they aid in conveying the meaning of a sentence effectively. Supra-segmental errors can be categorized into three distinct types: stress errors, rhythm errors, and intonation errors.

\paragraph{Stress:} Stress is the emphasis placed on certain syllables in a word or sentence. It is articulated by increasing the loudness, duration, and pitch of the stressed syllable. It can be categorized as \textbf{lexical stress}, if the stress is placed on syllables within the word, or \textbf{sentence stress} if the stress is placed on words within sentences. Mandarin learners of English has contrastive stress at the word-level that is absent in Korean, Mandarin speakers can have an advantage over Korean speakers in stress processing of English words \cite{wang2022segmental}. 

% Chinese learners of English encounter significant challenges when it comes to the stress in English pronunciation since Chinese is a tonal language \cite{han2013pronunciation}. 

\paragraph{Rythm:} Rythm is the pattern of stressed and unstressed syllables in a word or sentence. A language can be classified as either stress-timed or syllable-timed \cite{ohata2004phonological, matthews2014concise}. In stress-timed languages, the duration of stressed syllables tends to dominate the overall time required to complete a sentence. Conversely, in syllable-timed languages, each syllable receives an equal amount of time during production. For instance, when articulating an English sentence, the duration of sentence completion largely depends on the number of stressed syllables present. In contrast, the time needed to generate a Chinese sentence is determined by the total number of syllables, as all the syllables contribute to the recurring rhythmic pattern within the sentence.

\paragraph{Intonation:} Intonation encompasses pitch variations in speech. L2 learners of Vietnamese and Mandarin Chinese encounter significant difficulty in acquiring the distinct tones, particularly if their native language lacks tonality. As tonal languages, Vietnamese and Mandarin Chinese rely on different pitch patterns to convey distinct meanings, making it challenging for learners to accurately grasp and reproduce these tonal variations \cite{nguyen2014intonation, chen2015icall}.




% For example, the word "important" has two syllables, and the stress is typically placed on the first syllable. If a learner were to say "im-port-ant" instead of "im-por-tant", they would be placing the stress on the wrong syllable, which could change the meaning of the word.




