\subsection{Classification based on Acoustic Phonetics}
Classifier-based approaches has been explored both segmental and supra-segmental aspects of pronunciation. \textit{Segmental} approaches involve the use of classifiers targeting specific phoneme pair errors, utilizing different acoustic features such as MFCCs along with its first and second derivative, energy, zero-cross, and spectral features \cite{van2009automatic,huang2020mispronunciation}, with different techniques such as Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) \cite{truong2004automatic,strik2009comparing}, decision trees \cite{strik2009comparing}. \textit{Supra-segmental} approaches focus on detecting lexical stress and tones, utilizing features such as energy, pitch, duration, and spectral characteristics, with classifiers like GMMs \cite{ferrer2015classification}, SVMs \cite{chen2010automatic,shahin2016automatic}, and DNNs \cite{shahin2016automatic}. 

\subsection{Traditional Likelihood-based Scoring and GOP Formulation}
The initial likelihood-based MD algorithms aims to detect errors at the phoneme level using pre-trained HMM-GMM ASR models. Notably, \citet{kim1997automatic} introduce a set of three HMM-based scores, including likelihood scores, log posterior scores and segment-duration based score. Among these three, the log-based posterior scores are widely adapted due to its high correlation with human scores, and is also used to calculate the popular `goodness of pronunciation' (GOP) measure. 
The GMM-HMM based GOP scores can be defined by $GOP(p)=P(p|O) = \frac{p(O|p) \ P(p)}{\sum_{q} \ p(O|q)\ P(q)}$,
% the Equation \ref{eq:GOP}, 
representing the posterior probability of a target phone $p$ given a sequence of acoustic features $O$, considering a set of phones $Q$.
Moreover, these scores are further improved using forced alignment framework \cite{kawai1998call}. More details are presented in \citet{GOP_WITT}. 







