\subsection{Reformulation of GOP}
% \subsubsection{Segmental:}
\paragraph{Segmental:}
% Various likelihood-based algorithms aim at detecting errors at the phoneme level using pre-trained HMM-GMM ASR models. Notably, Kim et al. \cite{kim1997automatic} introduce a set of three HMM-based scores, while Kawai et al. \cite{kawai1998call} utilise log-likelihood scores within a forced alignment framework. These likelihood-based scoring approaches primarily involve comparing the scores obtained from forced alignment with those obtained from Viterbi decoding at the phoneme level, with the objective of identifying discrepancies. In a comprehensive study by Witt et al. \cite{GOP_WITT}, a thorough overview of diverse likelihood-based approaches is provided, the term "goodness of pronunciation" (GOP) is proposed then which encompasses these previous proposed likelihood-scores approaches and has gained widespread recognition within the field. Equation \ref{eq:GOP} defines the GOP based on a GMM-HMM ASR model. It represents the posterior probability of a target phone $p$ given a sequence of acoustic features $O$, considering a set of phones $Q$.

% \begin{equation}
% \label{eq:GOP}
% \begin{small}
% GOP(p)=P(p|O) = \frac{p(O|p) \ P(p)}{\sum_{q} \ p(O|q)\ P(q)}
% \end{small}
% \end{equation}

\citet{normalized} are first to propose a more effective reformulation of the base formulation of the GOP score . They introduce a scaling factor by normalizing the log-posteriors, as shown in Equation \ref{eq:probas}. This approach enhances the computation of the GOP score.

\begin{equation} 
    \label{eq:probas} 
    \begin{small} 
        GOP_r(p) = |\frac{p(o_t|p) P(p)}{\max_q p(o_t|q)}|
    \end{small} 
\end{equation}

Luo et al. develop a formulation of GOP by utilizing the selected state sequence obtained from the forward-backward algorithm \cite{luo2009analysis}. Building upon this formulation, Wang et al. adopt the GOP framework and incorporate error pattern detectors for phoneme mispronunciation diagnosis tasks \cite{wang2012improved}. Besides, and with the emergence of DNN in the field of ASR, Hu et al. demonstrate that using a DNN-HMM ASR for GOP yields improved correlation scores of 22\% and 15\% at the word and sentence levels, respectively, surpassing non-DNN models and GMM-HMM based acoustic models \cite{DNN1, DNN4, DNN5}. 

The GOP and its reformulation represent a significant milestone. It leverages pre-trained acoustic models on L1 and/or L2 without necessitating any L2 knowledge. Furthermore, it offers the advantage of being computationally efficient to calculate. However, it is important to note that these scores lack context-aware information that is crucial for accurate pronunciation analysis. To overcome this, Shi et al. \cite{CA-GOP} propose a context-dependent duration model to predict the duration of a given phoneme sequence. They introduce a duration factor, denoted as $\alpha_i$, which represents the phonetic mismatch between the reference and test utterances. Furthermore, a contextual factor called the Transition Factor is proposed by incorporating phone transitions inspired by the concept of entropy in information theory, as depicted in Equations \ref{eq:entropy} and \ref{eq:TA}. The formulated GOP score combines all the contextual scores, as illustrated in Equation \ref{eq:CAGOP}.

\begin{equation} 
    \label{eq:entropy} 
    \begin{small} 
        E_t = - \sum p(q_i|y_t)\: log(p(q_i|y_t)) 
    \end{small}
\end{equation} 

\begin{equation} 
    \label{eq:TA} 
    \begin{small} 
    TAScore(q_i) = \sum_{t} \frac{\frac{1}{E_t}}{\sum_{t'} \frac{1}{E_{t'}}} log (p(q_i|y_t)) 
    \end{small} 
\end{equation}

\begin{equation} 
    \label{eq:CAGOP} 
    \begin{small} 
    GOP(q_i) = (1-\alpha_i) * \: TAScore(q_i) 
    \end{small} 
\end{equation} 


Likewise, Sudhakara et al. present a context-aware GOP formulation by adding phoneme state transition probabilities (STP) to the GOP score calculation \cite{STP}. This modification, shown in Equation \ref{eq:STP}, leads to a significant improvement in computer-human correlation compared to the original GOP formulation, assuming all phonemes are equally likely.

\begin{equation} 
    \label{eq:STP} 
    \begin{small} 
        GOP(q_i) = \frac{1}{d_i} [log \: P(q_i|y_t) + log \: P(q_i|q_{i-1})] 
    \end{small} 
\end{equation} 

% The GOP represents a significant milestone. It leverages pre-trained acoustic models on L1 and/or L2 without necessitating any L2 knowledge. Furthermore, it offers the advantage of being computationally efficient to calculate.

While efforts have been made to improve the GOP, it is important to acknowledge that the GOP score still has limitations, specifically in its ability to identify specific types of mispronunciation errors. 


% \subsubsection{Supra-segmental:}
\paragraph{Supra-segmental:}
To evaluate the overall accuracy of a word or sentence, one common approach is to calculate the average GOP scores across phonemes \cite{kim1997automatic, STP}. However, relying solely on averaging GOP scores at the phoneme level is limited to assess prosodic features accurately. To address this limitation, a novel method proposed in \cite{10042421} suggests combining GOP scores for prosodic, fluency, completeness, and accuracy. This approach involves utilizing context-aware GOP in conjunction with dynamic time warping (DTW) matching of pitch contours. Specifically, a weighted average of the context tokens found in the audio file is used to compute the combined GOP scores, enabling a more comprehensive assessment of the word and the sentence. Besides, and inspired from GOP, \cite{tong2015goodness} propose Goodness of Tone (GOT) by computing a vector of confidence scores for all the possible lexical tones. The GOT is based on posterior probabilities of tonal phones, and giving promising result for non-native mandarin tone assessment.

