\subsection{End-to-End MD}

In the new era of DNNs, there are significant exploration by researchers in leveraging the power of these models and training End2End MD systems. These advancements involve various approaches such as extracting acoustic information or even utilizing raw speech directly as input. This shift towards DNN-based architectures and the utilization of acoustic features or raw speech data has revolutionized the field of MD, enabling more efficient and accurate detection of mispronunciations in speech.

\paragraph{Segmental:}

In \cite{li2017improving}, DNNs are trained to classify phonetic attributes such as place, manner, aspiration, voicing, and phone using FBANK vectors and their derivatives. These DNNs produce posterior probabilities which are subsequently combined with phone posterior probability. Additionally, phone-level time boundary information (using force-alignment) is incorporated as input for the LSTM mispronunciation detector. This integration enhances the performance and accuracy of the mispronunciation detection system. In contrast, \cite{kyriakopoulos2018deep} introduces a siamese network architecture with a bidirectional LSTM (BD-LSTM) model. This approach directly extracts distance metrics between pairs of phone instances from audio frames and employs them for pronunciation scoring.


