Furthermore, researchers have been actively exploring various research directions in the training of end-to-end DNN systems for phoneme sequence prediction from raw speech data. The availability of considerable amounts of MD datasets annotated at the phoneme level has fueled this avenue. A notable approach presented in \cite{leung2019cnn} introduces a CNN-RNN-CTC model, where the CNN is utilized to extract relevant features. The RNN captures sequential information, while the Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC) component effectively predicts the phoneme sequence without any alignment component dependency. Furtherly, \cite{9746604}, a triplet of features consisting of acoustic, phonetic, and linguistic embeddings are fused using a similar CNN-RNN structure with an additional attention mechanism (APL). This exploration of multiple input features has shown promising results. Numerous other advancements have followed, such as architectural modifications and the adoption of transformer encoder-decoder structures instead of the CNN-RNN model. An example is presented in \cite{wu2021transformer}, where CNN layers are combined with transformer blocks. These improvements have further enhanced the performance of the models. Likewise, PEPPANET is a transformer based MD model that can jointly model the dictation process and the alignment process, and it provides corresponding diagnostic feedback \cite{10022472}. In \cite{JIM}, GOP features are explored in a multi-task framework, wherein GOP features are combined with phoneme textual embeddings to predict a range of scores, including sentence prosodic scores, word scores, and phoneme scores. The combined features serve as input for a Transformer Encoder model. Building upon this approach, a subsequent study by \cite{3M} further enhances the score predictions by incorporating additional features derived from pre-trained self-supervised learning (SSL) models, energy and duration features at the phoneme level. The same architecture is followed in \cite{fan2023multifaceted}, using a Conformer encoder instead. Zhang et al highlight two limitations of these approaches \cite{zhang2023phonetic}. Firstly, current models often assume independence in predicted phonemes using CTC, which overlooks prominent mispronunciation patterns. Secondly, these models are restricted to training data from a language-specific phoneme set, making it difficult to distinguish accented sounds not present in the predefined set. To overcome these limitations, Zhang et al propose recurrent neural network transducer RNN-T model for MD. These models capture the temporal dependence of mispronunciation patterns. Additionally, an extended phoneme set and weakly supervised training strategy are introduced to enable the model to differentiate similar-sounding phonemes from different languages.

