Several approaches have been proposed for prosodic scoring in pronunciation models. In \cite{chen2018end}, an end2end solution is presented, which involves using DNNs to encode both lexical and acoustical cues for automatic feature learning. The architecture includes CNN layers followed by Bidirectional LSTMs (BD-LSTM) and attention mechanisms, the end goal is to predict sentence pronunciation scores. In \cite{lin2021deep}, the focus is on utilizing deep features directly from the acoustic model instead of relying on complex feature computations like GOP scores. A scoring module, incorporating a self-attention mechanism, is designed to model human scoring. A different approach is proposed in \cite{7404814}, where traditional time-aggregated features are replaced with time-sequence features, such as pitch, to preserve more information without requiring manual feature engineering. The paper proposes the use of a BD-LSTM model for fluency predictions. 

Towards lexical stress detection, several methods have been proposed to improve accuracy and performance. Among these methods, \cite{li2018automatic} focuses on supervised classification using syllable-based prosodic features, lexical features, and syntactic features trained with multi-distribution deep neural networks. They leverage maximum syllable loudness, syllable nucleus duration, dynamic pitch values, and binary encoded lexical and syntactic features. Building upon the need for long-distance contextual information, \cite{ruan2019end} proposes a sequence-to-sequence approach using the Transformer model. Their method translates audio feature sequences to phoneme sequences with lexical stress marks directly, utilizing the encoder-decoder structure. The training process involves the audio feature sequence and the corresponding phoneme sequence with lexical stress marks. During the detection process, the recognized phoneme sequence is restricted by the phoneme sequence of the utterance, without limitations on the lexical stress marks of each phoneme. Furthermore, \cite{korzekwa2020detection} introduces an attention-based neural network that significantly improves the detection of lexical stress errors in L2 English speech. Their method focuses on the automatic extraction of syllable-level features. By leveraging attention mechanisms, they achieve enhanced performance compared to baseline models.

Tone classification has received significant attention in Mandarin language learning due to the crucial role that tones play in Mandarin Chinese. To address the challenge of tone classification in Mandarin, several methods have been proposed. One approach involves training a DNN to classify speech frames into six tone classes \cite{ryant2014mandarin}. Inspired by this, DNNs have been used to map combined cepstral and tonal features to frame-level tone posteriors. These tone posteriors are then fed into tone verifiers to assess the correctness of tone pronunciation \cite{lin2018improving, li2018improving}. Another study utilizes CNN to classify syllables into the four Mandarin tones \cite{chen2016tone}. Similarly, ToneNet, a CNN-based network, is been introduced for Chinese syllable tone classification using mel-spectrogram as a feature representation. ToneNet employs a customized CNN and multi-layer perceptron for tone classification \cite{gao2019tonenet}. Additionally, bidirectional long short-term memory (BLSTM) based recurrent neural networks have been proposed as an alternative to DNNs for tone classification \cite{li2019improving}. BLSTMs are advantageous for capturing long-term dependencies in acoustic and prosodic features, enabling improved modeling of tone-level co-articulation and non-native tone production.
