\subsection{Transfer learning using self-supervised ASR models:}

Motivated by the recent success of self-supervised learning methods \cite{baevski2020wav2vec, hsu2021hubert, chen2022wavlm, 9893562} in speech recognition and related downstream tasks such as emotion recognition, speaker verification, and language identification \cite{chen2023exploring, fan2020exploring}, self-supervised approaches is employed also in MDD tasks for both segmental and supra-segemtal aspects. The model is trained exclusively on unannotated native data, and subsequently, linear classifiers are incorporated atop the model for fine-tuning. 

\paragraph{Segmental:}
In recent studies, wav2vec 2.0 has been employed as a pretraining method for MD in \cite{xu2021explore}. By utilizing canonical phones and aligning time extracted from a trained HMM-DNN using force-alignment, the models are subsequently fine-tuned on L2-ARCTIC annotated non-native data. The objective of this fine-tuning process is to determine whether the pronunciation is correct or not, utilizing cross entropy loss. However, it is important to note that this method heavily relies on time alignment and the use of an accurate pre-trained HMM-DNN to achieve accurate alignments. To overcome the dependency on time alignment, researchers have explored alternative approaches. In one study \cite{peng2021study}, a CTC-based wav2vec 2.0 is used to predict sequences based on human-labeled non-native data. Remarkably, this approach demonstrates promising performance without relying on time alignment. Building upon this work, Yang et al. \cite{yang2022improving} adopt the same proposed CTC wav2vec structure and propose an approach that leverages unlabeled L2 speech to enhance MDD performance through pseudo-labeling. In their recent study, Kheir et al. \cite{kheir2023multi} explore the utilization of mono- and multilingual pre-trained wav2vec encoders to capture different aspects of speech production with additional auxiliary tasks, including articulatory features sequences prediction, alongside the primary task of human-labeled phoneme sequence prediction. The approach achieve a well-balanced trade-off between recall and precision, surpassing existing state-of-the-art models. In a contrasting approach, the study presented in \cite{9746727} combines wav2vec 2.0 features and textual embeddings by jointly learning to predict the phoneme sequence and detect boundaries. 

