\subsection{Unsupervised Approaches}

It is important to note that the aforementioned approaches for deriving mispronunciation detection typically involve the need for expert knowledge, laborious manual labeling, or dependable ASR results, all of which come with significant costs. In contrast, recent years have witnessed considerable endeavors in unsupervised acoustic pattern discovery, albeit yielding sub-optimal outcomes. 
Lee et al. \cite{6424254} initially investigate a comparison-based approach that analyzes the extent of misalignment between a student's speech and a teacher's speech, without requiring linguistic expertise. Furthermore, in subsequent studies Lee et al. \cite{lee2015mispronunciation, lee2016personalized}, they explore the discovery of mispronunciation errors without utilizing non-native training data or expert input. Instead, they focus on analyzing the acoustic similarities across individual learners' utterances. Subsequently, they propose an n-best filtering method to resolve ambiguous error candidate hypotheses derived from acoustic similarity clustering. In another study \cite{mao2018unsupervised}, an unsupervised method to expand the phoneme set in L2 speech is proposed and then they apply k-means clustering on phoneme-based phonemic posterior-grams (PPGs) generated using a DNN-based acoustic-phonemic model (APM). More recently, Sini et al. \cite{sini2023phone} introduce a weighted dynamic time warping (DTW) alignment as an alternative to the GOP algorithm for predicting probabilities and the sequence of target phonemes. Their proposed method achieves comparable results to the GOP scoring algorithm.

