\paragraph{Hierarchical Evaluation Structure:}
We adhere to the hierarchical evaluation structure developed in \cite{qian2010capturing}, which has also been adopted in \cite{wang2015supervised} and it's the most used in recent segmental MD studies \cite{li2016mispronunciation}. As shown in Figure \ref{fig:tree-graph-mdd}, in hierarchical mispronunciation detection we distinguish between different outcomes. Specifically, true acceptance (TA) corresponds to the number of phones that are annotated and recognized as correct pronunciations. True rejection (TR) signifies the number of phones that are annotated as mispronunciations and correctly identified as such by CAPT systems. On the other hand, false rejection (FR) represents the number of phones that are recognized as mispronunciations even though the actual pronunciations are correct. False acceptance (FA) denotes the number of phones that are misclassified as correct pronunciations, but are actually mispronounced. For mispronunciation diagnosis, the primary focus is on cases of true rejection (TR). Those instances are examined to derive where diagnostic errors (DE) occur. The number of phones correctly classified as mispronunciations and accurately identified as matching the annotated phones is denoted as CD. As a result, we can calculate the false rejection rate (FRR), false acceptance rate (FAR), and diagnostic error rate (DER) using the following equations:



% The hierarchical evaluation structure introduced in [15], which has also been utilized in [43], is the most used evaluation metrics for MDD segmental error measuring. As shown in Figure \ref{fig:tree-graph-mdd}, after comparing the hypothesis phoneme sequence with the predicted phoneme sequence, the unit outcomes are classified as either true acceptance (TA) or true rejection (TR) for correct pronunciations, and as false rejection (FR) or false acceptance (FA) for incorrect pronunciations. When it comes to mispronunciation diagnosis, the focus is on cases of true rejection (TR), specifically examining those that involve diagnostic errors (DE). As a result, we can calculate the false rejection rate (FRR), false acceptance rate (FAR), and diagnostic error rate (DER) using the following equations:

\begin{equation}
FRR = \frac{FR}{TA + FR}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
FAR = \frac{FA}{FA + TR}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
DER = \frac{DE}{CD + DE}
\end{equation}


